{"key":"post-10129101","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>10129101</id>\n<content>The same way.&amp;nbsp; Bring your substrate or casing layer material to field capacity and load into plastic bags or jars.&amp;nbsp; Put in a pot of water and heat to boiling, while watching a meat thermometer in the center of the bag or jar.&amp;nbsp; When the temp reaches 140F, shut off the stove or reduce to lowest setting.&amp;nbsp; Check every few minutes and adjust the stove burner as necessary to keep the center of your substrate between 140F and 160F for one hour.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;No, I wasn't being sarcastic.&amp;nbsp; I just hate the idea of leaching the good stuff from manure by squeezing it out after over-hydration.&amp;nbsp; It's also much faster this way, since there's no draining or squeezing involved.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>10129108</next>\n<prev>10129031</prev>\n<first>10128854</first>\n<last>10134381</last>\n<when>1239208086</when>\n<utime>04/08/09 07:28 PM</utime>\n</post>"}